1.2 Data cleaning

youtube <- youtube %>% clean_names() # standardize column names, all starting with small cases

# Transform blank value into NA, necessary for the next functions to recognize blank spaces as missing values
for (col in names(youtube)) {
  if (is.factor(youtube[[col]]) || is.character(youtube[[col]])) 
  {
    youtube[[col]][youtube[[col]] == ""]  <- NA
  }
}

# Standardize data types, transforming some categorical variables into factor
youtube <- youtube %>% 
  mutate(
    created_month = factor(created_month, 
                           levels = c("Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec")),
    channel_age_category = factor(channel_age_category, levels = c("New", "Established","Veteran")),
    continent = as.factor(continent),
    channel_type = as.factor(channel_type),
    category = as.factor(category) 
  )

# Filter out invalid data
youtube_clean <- youtube %>%
  # video views as performance measure, only interested in channels with more than 0 video views 
  filter(video_views > 0) %>% 
  # drop rows where the total number of views is smaller than the views in the last 30 days
  filter(is.na(video_views_for_the_last_30_days) | video_views >= video_views_for_the_last_30_days) %>%
  # Youtube was founded in 2005, any channel older than that is dropped 
  filter(is.na(channel_age_years) |channel_age_years <= 20) 

# Transform unit, dividing by million for readability
youtube_clean <- youtube_clean %>% 
  mutate(subscribers_mil = subscribers/1e6,
         video_views_mil = video_views/1e6,) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-c(subscribers, video_views))

Standardize continents

# Use continent names instead of "Other" when info about country is available 
youtube_clean <- youtube_clean %>%
  mutate(
    continent = if_else(
      continent == "Other",
      countrycode(country, "country.name", "continent"),
      continent
    )
  )

# The package countrycode does not distinguish between South and North America but uses Americas instead.
# We first filter the columns which have Americas as entry and change those accordingly. 
youtube_clean%>%
  filter(continent == "Americas") %>%
  dplyr::select(country, continent)
##       country continent
## 1        Cuba  Americas
## 2 El Salvador  Americas
## 3    Barbados  Americas
## 4   Venezuela  Americas
## 5     Ecuador  Americas
## 6        Peru  Americas
## 7     Ecuador  Americas
youtube_clean <- youtube_clean %>%
  mutate(
    continent = case_when(
      country %in% c("Cuba", "El Salvador", "Barbados") ~ "North America",
      country %in% c("Venezuela", "Ecuador", "Peru") ~ "South America",
      TRUE ~ continent
    )
  )

# Check whether the transformation worked.
youtube_clean %>%
  filter(continent == "Other" | continent== "Americas") %>%
  dplyr::select(country, continent)
## [1] country   continent
## <0 rows> (or 0-length row.names)
# 0 observations with "Other" or "Americas".

2 EXPLORATION DATA ANALYSIS

2.1 Correlation between variables

# Heatmap

corr_results <- corr.test(
  youtube_clean[, c("avg_monthly_earnings","subscribers_mil", "video_views_mil", "uploads", 
                    "earnings_per_view", "sub_growth_rate_30d", "channel_age_years", 
                    "country_gdp_per_capita_est", "unemployment_rate",
                    "video_views_for_the_last_30_days", "population", "video_views_rank", "rank")],
  use = "pairwise"
)

r <- corr_results$r
p <- corr_results$p

# Convert matrices to long format
r_long <- melt(r)
p_long <- melt(p)

# Combine correlation and p-value data
heatmap <- left_join(r_long, p_long, by = c("Var1", "Var2"))
colnames(heatmap) <- c("x", "y", "r", "p")

# Create significance stars
heatmap$stars <- ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.001, "***",
             ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.01, "**",
             ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.05, "*", "")))

# Plot using ggplot2
ggplot(heatmap, aes(x, y, fill = r)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(9, "YlOrRd"))(200)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(r, 2)), size = 2.5, color = "black") + # correlation values
  geom_text(aes(label = stars, y = as.numeric(y) + 0.25), # stars (offset upward)
            color = "black", size = 2.5) +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1),
        axis.title = element_blank()) +
  labs(title = "Correlation Matrix with Significance Stars",
       fill = "r")

  group_by(channel_age_years) %>%

2.4 Word Analysis

#Word Analysis 

# Clean titles
youtube_clean <- youtube_clean %>%
  mutate(
    # Removes any characters that are not letters, numbers, or common punctuation
    title = gsub("[^a-zA-Z0-9 .,!?\\-:;'\"()]+", "", title, perl = TRUE), 
    # Removes any occurrences of the string "<NA>" from the title
    title = gsub("(<NA>)+", "", title) 
  )

# Stop words tibble
stop_tbl <- tibble(word = stopwords::stopwords("en"))

# Select top 30 channels per type and tokenize
tokens <- youtube_clean %>%
  group_by(channel_type) %>%
  slice_max(avg_monthly_earnings, n = 30) %>% # per channel type highest performing 30 channels
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(
    title = title %>%                      
      str_to_lower() %>%#lower case
      str_replace_all("[^a-z ]", " ") %>% # replace all non-alphabetic characters with space
      str_squish() # remove whitespace
  ) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, title, drop = FALSE) %>% # one word per column
  anti_join(stop_tbl, by = "word") # remove common stopwords

# Average words per channel type
avg_words <- tokens %>%
  filter(!is.na(word), channel_type != "") %>%
  count(channel_type, title) %>%
  # count average words in titles for each channel types
  summarise(avg_words = mean(n), .by = channel_type) 

overall_avg <- mean(avg_words$avg_words, na.rm = TRUE) # calculate average words of all channel types

# Visualization
ggplot(avg_words, aes(channel_type, avg_words)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue") +
  geom_hline(yintercept = overall_avg, linetype = "dashed", color = "red", linewidth = 1) +
  labs(x = "Channel type", y = "Words", title = "Average length of channel names") +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, size = 9),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 9),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 9),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 9)
  )

# TFIDF analysis
by_channel_type <- tokens %>%
  count(channel_type, word, sort = TRUE)

tfidf <- by_channel_type %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, channel_type, n) # Calculate tf-idf for words in each channel type

# Visualization
tfidf %>%
  group_by(channel_type) %>%
  slice_max(tf_idf, n = 5, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  filter(channel_type %in% c("Entertainment", "Music", "People", "Comedy", "Games", "Education", "News", "Howto")) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder_within(word, tf_idf, channel_type)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(word, tf_idf)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_wrap(~ channel_type, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_x_reordered() +
  labs(title = "Top words per channel type (tfidf)", x = NULL, y = "tfidf")

Chose log-transformed regression because log variables address skewness and show distribution closer to normal distribution

high_influence <- which(cooks > 4 / n)
